You can rewrite your story at anytime ☺️ 

I’ve never liked Christmas. I would try & decorate/get in the holiday spirit despite not loving it…it was still hard for me. I always felt so alone. I spent the last couple of years crying while decorating a tree. Whether I had a bf sitting right there on the couch or I was single, I was decorating alone. 

Documenting these moments as I rewrite my story & fall in love with life on my own & find joy in the things I once told myself I didn’t like 🖤

#alonenotlonely #christmascountdown

Have you ever been living in a moment that you KNOW you’re going to miss so much when its over? 

For years I was dreaming of just taking off & seeing where life took me. Honestly since I was a kid I wanted to be a free spirit. 

9 months ago I couldn’t stop thinking about just driving until I found a place I loved. 

6 months ago I made the commitment to do it.

3 months ago I drove away from my hometown with no plan & was absolutely terrified & excited at the same time. 

Then I ended up on this little island & was still terrified. I didn’t know anyone. What happened if I had an emergency? Everyone I could call was 3,000 miles away.

Now… 

I have more people I can count on here to help at anytime than I did back home 🥹

I walk across the street to my friends house to drive over to the gym every morning.

Then I walk just a couple more feet to the coffee shop. 

My neighbor behind me invited me over for a thanksgiving party and said just walk out your back door & we’ll be right there just walk through the yard.

My other neighbor calls me anytime there’s a rainbow or beautiful sunset so I can go look out my window.

This community & place is everything I ever dreamed of. It make just be for a season, but I know God placed me here for a reason ❤️

I hope the next 6 months go by a little bit slower 🥺🙏🏼
Or all the pieces comes together for me 🖤

 #movefromyourhometown #obx #outerbanks #islandlife #hatteras

Since this is the first year I actually feel jolly for the holiday seasons, I think these photos deserve a permanent spot on my feed. Even if it has nothing to do with fitness 😌

To me working out is so much more than just moving your body and trying to look as good as possible. 

I noticed that once I made working out a priority my whole life changed, truly 🖤

I felt more drive. More energy. More confidence & not just with my body, but with how I held myself which pushed me to higher my standards. I got raises in both jobs I was working at. My relationships got better. I made more & saved more money. I started showing up for ME. 

I’m a FIRM BELIEVER that when you look good, you feel good, and you DO GOOD. 

How could I show up looking & feeling my best when I hated what I saw in the mirror? 

When I didn’t want to leave my house/hang out with people because I wasn’t comfortable in anything I wore? 

If it wasn’t for finally hiring a coach & making my fitness a priority 7 years ago, I would not be here. 

I would not have been able to move across the country & experience these new adventures. 

And I most certainly would not be okay decorating my Christmas tree alone. 

Stop holding yourself back & take that step in bettering your health, mindset, and life 🖤💪🏼

Allow me to reintroduce myself 💁🏼‍♀️

I’ve spent a lot of my life riding this rollercoaster of feeling great & then being so depressed I want it all to end. 

If you’ve ever felt that way, it’s terrifying. 

One day I woke up & said okay dude… what are you going to do? Change everything or just give up? 

And I’ve never been a quitter 👊🏼 so I wrote down everything that I’ve been doing in my 26 years of life & said REBRAND YOUR LIFE. 

I do this with my business all the time! If something isn’t working properly, you analyze & scrap things/improve things. 

So I did that with my life. I shedded everything. I wanted to do everything differently. Because obviously everything I’ve done to that point in my life wasn’t working & getting me to where I wanted to be. 

Now this may seem extreme to you! But if you felt how I felt.. I needed extreme action. 

& let me tell you, it was so worth it 🥹

I’m almost 10 months sober, started another business & in the works of building a team, hit business goals I couldn’t for so long, feel better in my body then ever, mental health has been much better, I have the friendships I always dreamt of, I’m living in my dream place where I can walk to the coffee shop & beach in a matter of MINUTES. 

Oh and now I’m basically a brunette 🤣💁🏼‍♀️

It’s okay to change. Let go of that old identity you’ve clung to. The one that maybe you never wanted in the first place, but it was molded for you. 🖤

I’m trying to learn that If you grew up in a burning house.. ❤️‍🔥

You can build a house that isn’t on fire. 

You can find someone who doesn’t make you want to set It on fire. 

Just because chaos is familiar to you, doesn’t mean you have to stay in it. Create & find your peace.

Hi friend! I’m really proud of you for making it through another year 🖤

I know it was tough. Maybe you didn’t walk through HE🏒🏒with a smile, but you walked through anyways & that’s something to celebrate. 

I hope 2023 brings you more blessings & a little less tough lessons 😌

Just remember. Bad days build better days 🖤

I spent a lot of my life miserable. 

Miserable in jobs I worked. 
Miserable in my body.
Miserable in relationships. 

But breakthroughs come from the breakdowns. 

Sometimes you have to hit rock bottom, to bounce back up. 

My journey to building the life I always dreamt of started when I was 22. 

I was working at a coffee shop barely getting by and my health was quickly deteriorating.

I basically lived at the bars, I was broke from staying out till closing time and throwing down shots, I lived off coffee shop bagels, dominos pizza, and fast food. 

My whole body ached from gaining weight and not taking care of it. 

I was looking for temporary love and attention in all the wrong ways. 

I had this dream of competing in the local body building competition, which was something I was working towards before I went on this downward spiral. 

A regular at the coffee shop I was working at pointed me in the right direction. I hired my first trainer. I had to pick up a second job and ask my dad to help me out in order to afford him. 

I was waking up at 4am to workout before I worked all day. 

I started staying in on the weekends, I was finally learning how to cook my meals, & I was starting to find myself again. 

Once I made my health & fitness journey a priority, everything fell into place for me. 

I got a great paying job, started getting out of debt, got a nice car, invested in a personal trainer course, & started living the life I thought was too far out of reach. 

It’s safe to say fitness saved my life & gave me a purpose. 

My only regret? I waited so long to ask for help and start taking care of myself.

I don’t know who needs to hear this, but if you’re too focused on changing EVERY little thing in your lifestyle in order to lose weight, you’re going to burn out. 👀

I’m so proud of myself 🥹

Full transparency… it’s not always easy. 

This last month I ran into 2 times I found myself wanting a drink. 

When my car started having issues after I was driving through a winter storm I had a full on breakdown in the gas station parking lot. 

I went into buy brake fluid and just stared at the alcohol. It felt illegal to look at it. It was a weird feeling. Everyone else was just having a normal night while I was sitting there battling with myself. 

I was so far away and just got a hotel. 

Nobody would know if I broke down. 

It would numb all my emotions. 

Instead I grabbed some redbull. 

I decided to pull myself together so I could get work done & continue to push myself forward in my business & life. 

The exact reason I stopped drinking in the first place. 

When I got to my hotel the lady at the counter knew I had been crying & was so sweet. 

When I got to my room I sat in the hot shower & bawled for a while. Then I said no more. You worked too hard to breakdown on the bathroom floor again. Life is tough, but I’m tougher. 

I turned the water on freezing cold & shocked my system. 

Then I got myself together & I’m totally okay. 

The one thing being sober has taught me, is that I can deal with anything. I don’t need to numb myself anymore. It doesn’t help at all.

Now I can process & move on. 

And if you relate to this I’m proud of you.

The last 2 months have been a serious rollercoaster. 

I had a business coach tell me years ago “new levels, brings new devils” 

It took me a while to understand what this truly meant… here’s what I came up with👇🏼

When we reach this new exciting goal or “level” in our life that we haven’t before, it’s amazing! It’s like DANG I finally made it!! 

However, some fear can creep up because automatically our brain goes “danger I’ve never experienced this new level before & we have no idea what to expect.. can you even maintain this or will it all fall apart?” here’s where the devil comes in. 

We start subconsciously filling our head with doubt & anxiety to the point where we basically manifest failure. 

Now you probably don’t recognize this happening. I want you to think back on a time you did something new, did you ever question if it’ll work out? Did you spend more time stressing about it then celebrating and working towards it? 

All those things you spent your energy worrying about..why wouldn’t they come true now?! You were so focused on the bad outcome, that you made it come your way. 

Now this isn’t to say every bad thing that happens is your fault!!! I do believe things happen for a reason, so whether you feared this happening or not, it’s just a lesson pushing you towards other things 🫶🏻

This is why I think it’s very important that you take time to journal every day & get super clear with your vision, your plans, and your emotions. Every day I write out how I’m feeling and dissect where those emotions are coming from. Yes, even the good emotions! 

You need to learn how to control your mind & emotions and how to pivot at anytime 💫

Wow. Wow. WOW. 

I’ve spent the last month screaming at God wondering why it feels like everything is falling apart. 

There’s this thing about “healing” that NOBODY TALKS ABOUT.. 

It gets really, really ugly. 

I keep reminding myself that when it feels like everything is falling apart, it may actually be falling into place. 

I have a long list of things that just happened in the last month that sent me into the worst depressive episode of my entire life. 

But I’m not ready to go into detail of all that. I just want to let you know that without any warning life can get very hard. Here are my tips to break out of the hard times 🖤👇🏼

1. Find your safe haven. Something that keeps you going. I was working out 2-3 times a day just to help release negative emotions.

2. It’s absolutely so important to have people in your life who truly care 🥺 who’s going to notice when you go ghost? So grateful for everyone who reached out & checked on me ❤️

3. Seek out help. Call your doctor or find therapy. You can google lots of options! I know some are expensive but there’s lots of resources that can help you, even if it’s just a book for now it’s better than nothing. 

4. Push yourself to take care of yourself. I know when you’re depressed even showering seems like the hardest task. Go buy new self care stuff. I bought all new things so it was exciting to get ready & I felt so much better when I was clean & smelled good 😌 same goes for cleaning! Get a new candle, anything. 

Just remember.. bad days build better days 🥺🖤

ONE YEAR SOBER 😌🥂

Last year I woke up on this day hung over & decided to stop drinking! 

I had tried to stop before. I still don’t know how this time was any different or any easier than the times before. 

I asked myself if this was the life I wanted to live & if I continue to not reach my goals because I’m choosing to get drunk, is that going to be okay with me? 

My birthday was in a week & every bday I reflect on my life & set new goals. 

I really didn’t want to go ANOTHER year where I look back & say “wow you didn’t do anything you said you would…”

So I changed. 

It wasn’t easy at all. 

But let me tell you… sitting here reflecting now before my bday again & saying “HOLY SMOKES IM SO PROUD OF MYSELF” is way better than feeling angry & beat down. 

If you’ve been following me, you know this year has been insane & full of so many things I never thought I’d do. ☺️

The second I decided to stop drinking, my life came back together. 

I explain a lot more in my YouTube video so find me over there: (Caseyfitcakes) 

I put 16 candles on the cake I baked myself because there were 16 significant times in the year that I thought “wow a beer would make this a whole lot easier” 

For the most part I didn’t think about drinking at all. I still think it sounds awful! 

The times I wanted to drink were when I was dealing with emotions I’ve suppressed for so long or stressful events that popped up. 

It was a huge shift for me when I realized I only ever drank to escape things. 

-anxious thoughts at events 
-stress in life 
-escape a bad day

I spent a lot of my life miserable. 

Miserable in jobs I worked. 
Miserable in my body.
Miserable in relationships. 

But breakthroughs come from the breakdowns. 

Sometimes you have to hit rock bottom, to bounce back up. 

My journey to building the life I always dreamt of started when I was 22. 

I was working at a coffee shop barely getting by and my health was quickly deteriorating.

I basically lived at the bars, I was broke from staying out till closing time and throwing down shots, I lived off coffee shop bagels, dominos pizza, and fast food. 

My whole body ached from gaining weight and not taking care of it. 

I was looking for temporary love and attention in all the wrong ways. 

I had this dream of competing in the local body building competition, which was something I was working towards before I went on this downward spiral. 

A regular at the coffee shop I was working at pointed me in the right direction. I hired my first trainer. I had to pick up a second job and ask my dad to help me out in order to afford him. 

I was waking up at 4am to workout before I worked all day. 

I started staying in on the weekends, I was finally learning how to cook my meals, & I was starting to find myself again. 

Once I made my health & fitness journey a priority, everything fell into place for me. 

I got a great paying job, started getting out of debt, got a nice car, invested in a personal trainer course, & started living the life I thought was too far out of reach. 

It’s safe to say fitness saved my life & gave me a purpose. 

My only regret? I waited so long to ask for help and start taking care of myself.
